{"key":"processedPost-9515640","value":{"id":9515640,"first":8648068,"last":9516679,"when":1230619532,"utime":"12/30/08 08:45 AM","content":"We all know cubensis doesn't even require a casing layer, so it's really moot to argue one way or the other what is best.&nbsp; With species that DO require a casing layer to fruit, plain verm won't cut the mustard.&nbsp; There's beneficial bacteria in peat that help stimulate pinsets, which are missing with verm.&nbsp; <br /><br />I've ruffled a lot of feathers lately by stating verm is a nutritious food for fungi.&nbsp; We all know plain verm casing layers will support cobweb, but they also support cubensis and many other species of beneficial fungi.&nbsp; You can take a small jar of grain spawn, mix it well with verm, and get a huge flush.&nbsp; It's not as good as coir or horse manure, but verm definitely isn't inert, even though it's mineral. It's a great addition to any substrate material, and not just for holding water. Go figure.<br />RR","title":"Re: Just to make you mad - my opinion on casings... feel free to flame.. haha"}}